Men. 1 5 5 liti- gium tibist cum uxore: eo mi abs te cauco cautius. Pseud. 474 cauen- dumst mi abs te irato.

121. murm sese msere mauo- let. Note the alliteration: misc-re belongs to moriri. From morior Plautus has the infin. moriri, not mori, six times. In verbs of the class to which morior belongs it is in the infin. only that a fourth- conjugation form occurs. filori occurs twice in MSS. but is unten- able in both passages. Yet beside moriri is found emori as the regular form, e.g. v. 810. Similarly from the compounds os gradior the Plautine infins. are aggredit-i, con· grediri, egredi ri, progrediri, but
